text.text: A Guide to South Kensington

text.html: Doormen in all black; Bentleys in all black; American Express cards in all black. Welcome to South Kensington - no hats and hoods around here, partner. That’s cool though, we aren’t the ones to judge. Sometimes you’ve got to appreciate the finer things in life, and we can scrub up and rub shoulders with the best of 'em when we try. So we tried. Dearest South Kensington, we’ve only gone and had it large. Much obliged.

Best for… pushing the boat out and treating yourself

tip.text: Holy moly. This très chic French-Italian restaurant from Alain Ducasse is summin else. Waiters in bowties and converse glide round tables of swanky diners whilst the maître d’ charms their pants off. The sea bass carpaccio is godly, the spelt with girolles is chuffing amazing and the lamb with seasonal veg is parfait. Don’t dodge dessert; try the strawberry soup and the Willy Wonka-esque tart from the Alain Ducasse chocolate factory with a glass of French Maury dessert wine. Orgasmique.

text.html: Maybe you’re fancy. Maybe it’s your Aston Martin out front with the tinted windows and gold rims, and maybe the doormen at the Bulgari know you on first name terms. Maybe. Probably not though, but there’s nothing wrong with that. There’s a world famous chef’s (Alain Ducasse) gourmet restaurant in there and it’s not as $$$$ as you’d assume... so book a table, put on your finest dinner jacket and act like you belong.

Best for… a cheeky tipple on a darling mews

tip.text:
You’ll find this cosy pub at the end of a delightful, cobbled mews in South Kensington. Expect to feel a world away from the hustle and bustle of the West End and to fill your belly with beer and food to your heart’s content. The taps here aim to showcase all sorts, from small brewers to international beers and everything in between.

Food offerings at The Queens Arms take the form of traditional British pub grub. You can tuck into the likes of sustainably caught hake; steak, pancetta and porter ale pies; fish and chips and, of course, a big ol’ Sunday roast. There’s a “how to distill your own spirits” diagram up in the bar so be sure to bring your notebook.

text.html: West London is all about romantic little cobbled streets; they make us feel like we’re slap bang in the middle of a Hugh Grant flick. Well, The Queens Arms pub can be found hidden at the end of one of these delightful mews in South Kensington, ideal for a cheeky pint-stop while you’re out exploring.

Best for… a bite and a breather while you’re out being cultured

tip.text:
Art or no art, this 19th century gallery cafe is worth a pilgrimage to. After all, it wouldn’t be very fitting if the V&A had a bog standard cafe would it? Well it doesn’t, unless your local one can boast stained glass, mosaic walls, chandeliers and a grand piano…? Didn’t think so. Best leave the impressive stuff to the experts (a.k.a. this lot).

The self-service area may be considerably less lavish than the dining rooms, but what it lacks in style it makes up for in selection: cakes, loose leaf teas, a hot food counter, a delicatessen, sandwiches, beers, a bloody wine bar - and then some (!). The food is overpriced just like any other gallery cafe but you can expect a decent range of refreshments. And yes, you can either take your bites among the mosaics or out front in the lovely garden area.

text.html: If you’re out in South Ken seeing about a spot of culture then chances are you’ll find yourself in the Victoria & Albert Museum. That’s all very well and we certainly urge you to seek out some history, but you’re gonna need a spot to rest your weary pins in there (what with all the walking and standing and observing and chin scratching). This is that place: shitloads of food and drink in an aptly grandiose setting.

tip.text:
A London legend and a destination for traditional Polish food in South Ken, Daquise has been dishing out dumplings (and plenty of other Polish delicacies) for the past 60 years.

Its reputation as one of London's best Polish restaurants is bolstered by its fans - the likes of Roman Polanski and Edward Raczynski (the exiled President of Poland) have been known to eat here.

Come for dishes like Salmon Tartare and Hunters Stew and stay for the impressive choice of vodka.

text.html: A spot officers used to grab coffees in during the war, boy does this quaint Polish restaurant feel like a time warp. You’ll likely catch the ancient owner chin-wagging with an elderly pal towards the back of the restaurant - he’s friendly so don’t be afraid to say hi. Historic reminders of WWII include a number of black and white photos and actual bullet-holes in one of the walls (behind glass panelling).

Best for… that sugar tho

tip.text:
Éclairs, but not as you know them. Expect to be wowed by this elegant patisserie in South Kensington: this isn’t your regular French classic found in Paul, or Maison Blanc, these are tiny works of art.

Delicate morsels are arranged in a dazzling array of flavours: think pistachio, strawberries and cream, and Tahitian vanilla. No expense is spared; the patisserie is topped with all manner of edible embellishments such as gold leaf, fresh fruit and chocolate nibs – good luck choosing what flavours you want to try. If you really are struggling, go for the yuzu passionfruit which is both deliciously tangy and sweet.

text.html: Sometimes you’ve just gotta take the safety reins off your inner child and let ‘em run wild. This is absolutely the place to do that: if all the bright colours don’t stimulate you then at least the sugar will have you bouncing off the walls. Indulge, indulge, indulge. We’re fully drooling right now…

Best for… a skylit Indian supper

tip.text:
This spot is way smarter than your local curry house: skylights, hanging plants and daaamn fine cocktails. Bombay Brasserie’s head chef has been knocking about on these premises since ‘91, so it’s probably safe to assume he knows his way around a spice rack. You can also expect the hella freshness of the ingredients to come through in the flavours of the food.

We don’t know about you but we can’t go for Indian food without getting something outta the clay oven. Here, we’d likely go for the kasundi monkfish with mustard from Calcutta. You won’t find any kormas or tikka masalas on this menu, but fear not: everything sounds incredible. Not the cheapest, but this is South Ken after all.

text.html: If a top floor dining room complete with skylights and hanging plants isn’t romantic or swanky enough for you then you’re probably very regal indeed. But for us average Joes this is pretty damn impressive. If you ever feel like treating yourself to sublime Indian food in a stunning setting then yeah, go here.

Best for… sippin’ on rare Italian wines

tip.text:
Wine-shop by day, lively bar by night, Bruno’s joint was the second of the ‘Little-Italy’ establishments on Old Brompton Road.

With atmospheric lighting, electro-swing playing in the background and black and white Italian films on the box, this spot is perfect for a date. You'd do well to nestle down in their pair of Jacobsen-style chairs with an aperitivo-style platter (premium cold cuts, cheeses, breads and plump olives) and a glass or two of their own-made 'Favorite' white wine (£5.50 for 125ml) – grande!

text.html: You might’ve noticed, walking around the area and whatnot, that South Kensington definitely isn’t in the Med. Does that mean you don’t deserve fantastic, rare Italian wines? Of course not. What about nice-ass cheeses and charcuterie? Hell no, you deserve that stuff. Enter Bruno (legend), who opened up Vini Italiani to give us exactly that - and that’s why we love him.

Best for… posh Polish plates

tip.text:
On the ground floor of a high-end Polish community club on Exhibition Road sits Ognisko. Despite its airs and graces, it’s a warm and inviting spot. Order their incredible chilli beetroot martini from the bar before rubbing shoulders with Polish aristocracy in the dining area.

We'd strongly advise ordering the pelmeni dumplings stuffed with veal and pork for starters, and for mains choose between something traditional and hearty like the bigos sausage stew or something more befitting the interiors like the grilled sea bass with fennel, apple and caper salad. Finish things off with a flavoured vodka - they have a ridiculous choice ranging from caramel to horseradish and honey.

text.html: Seems like South Ken has a bit of a Polish thing going on and we’re embracing it to the maxxxx. Ognisko is grand, full stop. Classy cocktails, lots of white, and a huge terrace overlooking gorgeous communal gardens (Kensington has ‘em in abundance). Tuck into your lunch out here, glass of wine in hand, and feel like absolute royalty.

Best for… much matcha

tip.text:
Healthy lifestyle is central to this Japanese cafe and matcha bar, run by mother and son team Manami and Louis. After realising good quality Japanese food was always mega spenny in London, they decided to bring us a little taste of the action, with premium products at more reasonable price points.

Get involved with colourful and wholesome bento boxes, sushi bowls, rice bowls and comforting curry bowls - we had a katsu number that really took the edge off. And then there's the green stuff, the whole reason you're here: matcha. Made with premium leaves, grown in the shade, hand picked and ground whole - there's all sorts of health benefits stuffed into this one, along with a subtle sweet taste. Whether you go for a matcha shot (the most traditional serving), a tea or latte, you're sure to get that caffeine kick without any of the jitters of coffee. This lot have won awards for specialising in the above, so you're truly in very safe hands.

It's also mixed into tarts, cakes, shakes and brownies, as well as a perfectly balanced soft serve. Sweet and bitter in all the right places, we couldn't get enough.

text.html: Tombo is keeping the people of South Ken well-supplied with delicious, healthy and colourful treats. Ideal for a lunchtime bite; grab a sushi bowl and follow it up with a spot of bespoke mochi ice cream why don’t you? These guys are crazy about their matcha green tea (award winning), so it’d probably make sense to dabble in a splash of that, too.

Best for… winning everything at steak

tip.text:
How does dining in an actual butcher shop tickle you? Don't be put off, because this is a proper steak experience - all the meat at Macellaio is Italy's finest, which is good because it's used to decorate the place. They use Fassone beef for the steaks, which are all massive cuts, and simple, powerful flavours to garnish them like gorgonzola, or Tuscan extra virgin olive oil with salt.

A nice touch is how they pair up specific wines for you, depending on what cut you choose, and how rare you like it. Don't worry, they also serve a pasta menu if you're not a meat head.

text.html: You’ve been traipsing around South Ken all day; you’ve smashed out some museums; maybe you even went to Harrods. Good on ya. What do you need now? A seeerious steak is what. Yeah it’s a butchers, but that should only be seen as an encouraging sign. These guys know exactly what’s going down on the beef scene: peruse the shop, pick a slab and they’ll grill that up for you with a choice of simple, powerful accompanying flavours.

tip.text: The Fernandez and Wells to top all Fernandez and Wells’. This shop stocks the best from all the others - so whether you’re in a mad morning rush or just wanna have a nice sip and snack while you knock out a bit of remote working, the options here are top notch. Freshly made juices, eye-opening coffee, delicious sandwiches made to order, plus a variety of breads, cakes, wines…. ran out of breath, soz.
